    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1941-04-07T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1941-04-07T00:00:00-05:00" n="502"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d502">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">890G.00/545</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">Memorandum of Telephone Conversation, by Mr. Gordon P. Merriam
                        of the Division of Near Eastern Affairs</hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">[<placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>,] <date calendar="gregorian" when="1941-04-07">April 7,
                            1941</date>.</dateline>
                </opener>
                <table>
                    <row>
                        <cell rendition="#nowrap #top">Participants:</cell>
                        <cell rendition="#hanging">Mr. Nevile Butler, Counselor of the British
                            Embassy</cell>
                    </row>
                    <row>
                        <cell/>
                        <cell rendition="#hanging">Mr. Murray<note n="19" xml:id="d502fn19">Wallace
                                Murray, Chief of the Division of Near Eastern Affairs.</note>
                        </cell>
                    </row>
                </table>
                <p>Mr. Murray referred to the British Embassy’s <hi rend="italic">aide-mémoire</hi>
                    of April 5, 1941, in which the hope was expressed that this Government would
                    withhold recognition from the new Gailani Government in Iraq and so instruct its
                    representative in Baghdad. Mr. Murray stated that we had just received a
                    telegram from our Minister in Baghdad,<note n="20" xml:id="d502fn20">
                        <hi rend="italic">Supra.</hi>
                    </note> apparently based upon a somewhat different view of the situation from
                    that which had prompted the Embassy’s <hi rend="italic">aide-mémoire</hi>, to
                    the effect that in the opinion of the British Ambassador there, a formal
                    decision by the British Government either to recognize or not to recognize the
                    Gailani regime was open to serious objections. It therefore seemed undesirable
                    for us to take a step which in the opinion of Sir Kinahan Cornwallis it would be
                    unwise for his own Government to take at this time.</p>
                <p>Mr. Butler agreed.</p>
            </div>
